<TITLE> Swine flu suspects advised to get treatment </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 1 (bdnews24.com)The government has advised swine flu suspects to get treatment immediately instead of waiting for confirmation of the H1N1 virus. "The situation to panic has not emerged yet. We have to take precautionary measures," health minister AFM Ruhal Haq told reporters after an inter-ministerial meeting at the Secretariat. "It is not possible to diagnose and treat all in health centres. The risky patients will be treated only," he said. Thirty-four fresh cases of swine flu were detected countrywide on Tuesday, pushing the official count of people infected by the virus to 247, the minister said. The figure was 213 until Monday. The government on Monday confirmed the first H1N1 death in Bangladesh. Doctors at Lab Aid Hospital in Dhaka said the victim was a 35-year old woman Mitali Chakravarty of Savar died at around 10.30pm on Sunday night. On the death, the minister said the patient died because she had been given wrong treatment. Haq said the ministries are working to aware people about swine flu and some 5,000 physicians have been provided training. In addition, doctors and health centres in Dhaka and at district and upazila levels have been instructed to provide patients proper advice on the virus. Education minister Nurul Islam Nahid told reporters that the situation was not so dire as to order schools shut. He suggested informing the health or education ministry if any student was suspected to be carrying the virus. "The education institutions are being closed on account of Ramadan. The swine flu panic has no relation with the vacation," he added. bd
